{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774290640,"nonce":"25n3q0QpQGOcXGSyY9iO/wjeO04=","message":"## Deep-Dive Analysis Update (Opus)\n\n### Mathematical Framework\n\n**Mutual information decomposition**: Define I_adapt(k) = I(u_k; θ | ς, s) — the mutual information between control output at time k and the perturbation parameter θ, conditioned on SISU and goal. A purely robust controller has I_adapt(k) = 0 for all k.\n\n**Critical limitation**: In closed-loop systems, nonzero I_adapt is necessary but NOT sufficient for adaptation. High feedback gains mechanically cause outputs to correlate with θ (because feedback carries θ information and a high-gain controller amplifies this). Must compare observed I_adapt against what robustness-only would produce as a side effect.\n\n**Jacobian test**: Compute ∂J_cl/∂ς (should be nonzero for both mechanisms) and ∂J_cl/∂θ (nonzero only under adaptation, after removing mechanical coupling). GRU Jacobian eigenvalue structure should vary with ς but not systematically with θ under robustness.\n\n**Spectral distinction**: Robustness = reduced peak sensitivity gain broadly (||T(z;ς_high)||_∞ \u003c ||T(z;ς_low)||_∞). Adaptation = structured gain reduction specific to training perturbation class spectral characteristics.\n\n**Null-space connection**: SISU perturbation at steady state producing null-space (not potent-space) changes is consistent with robustness (configuring response without generating force). Adaptive changes would be output-potent.\n\n### Enhanced Experimental Designs\n\n**Error-clamp trials (STRONGEST probe)**: Clamp effector to nominal trajectory, measure lateral forces. Adaptive: systematic compensatory forces persist (hidden state encoded θ-hat). Robust: approximately zero lateral force (nothing in feedback to react to). This directly separates estimation-based from feedback-based compensation.\n\n**Hidden-state decoding**: Train linear decoder to predict θ from h_k at each timestep. R²(k) increasing over time = adaptation. Compare against decoding from y_k alone — excess R² = active estimation beyond passive sensory information. This is the implementable version of I_adapt(k).\n\n**Enhanced regression**: Don't just regress forces on θ — regress RESIDUALS after removing the component explained by current feedback y_k. The formula: u_k = α + β_y·y_k + β_θ·θ + ε. If β_θ significant after conditioning on y_k, that's genuine adaptation.\n\n**Frozen-hidden-state**: Freeze GRU state at timestep k_freeze, allow feedback to continue. Performance degrades → network relies on evolving h (adaptation). Performance preserved → state-dependent gain structure suffices (robustness).\n\n**Temporal accumulation**: Delay perturbation onset by T_delay. Robustness: performance independent of T_delay. Adaptation: improves with T_delay only if perturbation present during delay.\n\n**Cross-perturbation generalization**: Train on curl, evaluate on constant (and vice versa) AS A FUNCTION OF SISU. Robustness: partially transfers. Adaptation: does not transfer.\n\n**Direction reversal enhancement**: Use CONSTANT fields (not curl) to eliminate velocity-dependence confound. Vary t_flip — adaptation shows larger overshoot for later flips (more committed to estimate); robustness is independent of t_flip.\n\n**SISU-high catch trials enhancement**: PAI-ASF training is symmetric over θ, so directional force bias shouldn't appear even under adaptation. Better: use brief perturbation pulse then remove — adaptive shows aftereffects; robust does not.\n\n### The Continuum Question\n\nThe distinction IS a continuum, not binary. GRU update gates smoothly interpolate between \"react to current input\" (robustness) and \"maintain estimate\" (adaptation). Same computation serves both functions simultaneously.\n\n**Two-dimensional characterization**:\n1. Impedance axis: how much do feedback gains change with ς? (from Jacobian analysis)\n2. Estimation axis: how much θ-information in h_k beyond current feedback? (from decoding)\n\nEach network occupies a point in this 2D space.\n\n### Ceiling Analysis Methodology\n\n**Oracle method** (requires retraining):\n1. Oracle Robust: perturbation randomized every M timesteps (unestimable but low-frequency)\n2. Oracle Adaptive: θ given as additional network input\n3. Adaptation fraction = (L_standard - L_oracle_robust) / (L_oracle_adaptive - L_oracle_robust)\n\n**Quick method** (no retraining): direction-reversal performance ≈ robustness-only; standard performance includes both. Gap estimates adaptation contribution.\n\n**Information-theoretic**: Decode θ from h_k, then test if the information is USED — run with h from wrong-θ trial + y from correct trial. If performance similar → information present but unused.\n\n### Recommended Priority\n\n1. Error-clamp trials — cleanest single probe\n2. Hidden-state decoding — quantitative I_adapt measurement\n3. Enhanced regression — uses existing eval data\n4. Direction-reversal with constant fields — intuitive, publishable\n5. Oracle-robust training — definitive ceiling (requires retraining)\n6. Cross-perturbation generalization — already planned\n7. Frozen-hidden-state — mechanistic insight\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}